Banknote Authentication

In this problem, I load, explore, visualize, and comment on data that describes bank notes that are both counterfeit and not counterfeit.

# load data
url <- "http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00267/data_banknote_authentication.txt"
banknote.df <- read_delim(url,",", col_names = c("moment2","moment3","moment4","entropy","class"))
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   moment2 = col_double(),
##   moment3 = col_double(),
##   moment4 = col_double(),
##   entropy = col_double(),
##   class = col_integer()
## )

Describe the data set attributes:

col_name attribute_name
moment2 variance of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
moment3 skewness of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
moment4 curtosis of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
entropy entropy of image (continuous)
class class (integer)

The data set has 1372 rows or observations and 5 columns or variables. The predictor variables are moment2, moment3, moment4, and entropy. The response variable is class.

Now present a summary of the data, complete with data types and measures of central tendency and dispersion: (Note: I convert the class variable from an integer to a factor. I run this analysis from the perspective of determining which banknotes are counterfeit: 0 equals no (not counterfeit), 1 equals yes (counterfeit).)

banknote.df$class <- factor(banknote.df$class, levels=c(0,1),
                            labels=c("no", "yes"))


# summarize data
banknote.skim <- data.frame(skim(banknote.df))
banknote.skim$value <- as.integer(banknote.skim$value)

banknote.skim.tranform <- banknote.skim %>% 
  filter(stat %in% c("missing","complete","n","n_unique","min","max","median","sd")) %>%
  spread("stat","value") %>% 
  select(-c(level))

kable(banknote.skim.tranform)

The scatterplot above shows a few interesting features:

  • the distribution of moment2 and moment3 seem to be more normal than the other variables
  • moment3 and moment4 seems to have a strong, negative linear correlation between them
  • there seems to be a visible distinction in how moment2 and moment3 are grouped by those that are counterfeit (Yes) and those that are not counterfeit (No)

Given that moment2 and moment3 seem to have close to constant variability, much of the variability in the class variable can probably be explained by these two variables. In other words moment2 and moment3 are more likely to be more predictive with respect to discriminating real and counterfeit bank notes.

This is probably not an easy problem to solve given that the data really only have one metric, Wavelet Transformed image, and the variables are really just a transformation of the 2nd to 4th moments of that metric about the mean. Different measurements of the bank notes may yield better predictions.

My guess is that there would be a high error rate in the data set, at about 75%. And since there is only one metric being used to determine counterfeit bank notes, I would expect a high error rate. The tradeoffs with a given level of error comes down to what would happen when Type I and Type II errors occur.

Assume the null hypothesis is that a sample bank note is not counterfeit. For Type I errors, rejecting the null hypothesis when it is true will lead bank examiners to conclude that there are fewer counterfeit bank notes in circulation, thus raising the cost of penalty from the government if those bank notes are traced back to the bank.

For Type II errors, failing to reject the null hypothesis when it is false will also be costly as the bank may take more bank notes out of circulation than is necessary. Though this cost would almost certainly be less than the cost borne by Type I errors.

The scatterplot above shows a few interesting features:

  • there are distinct differences in the distributions of all the weight variables, especially weight.shucked and weight.shell
  • length, diameter, and height have very strong, positive linear correlation among them
  • length has a strong positive linear correlation with all other variables except for sex

Given that all weight variables seem to show a distinct difference in distribution among the sex of the snail, much of the variability in the rings variable can probably be explained by these variables, particularly weight.shucked and weight.shell. In other words weight.shucked and weight.shell are more likely to be more predictive with respect to determining the age of the abalone snail.

Though boxplots grouped by sex are present in the pair-wise XY-scatterplots above, I will create two other boxplots with a sample of continuous data using the geom_boxplot() function in ggplot2.

cut <- 0.2

# length by rings
ggplot(abalone.df, aes(x=length, y=rings)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="steelblue", aes(group = cut_width(length, cut))) +

  theme_linedraw()

Tibbles

Tibbles are opinionated data.frames that adjust some of the legacy behaviors of R for data.frames. For instance, a tibble never changes the type of the inputs (e.g., if working with Census FIPS codes, it wont convert them to numerical values even though they are strings), it never changes the names of variables, and it never creates row names. If using the tidyverse package, functions in that package produce tibbles as its data.frame outputs. You can also create a new tibble from individual vectors with tibble().

There are two main differences between a tibble and a data.frame: printing and subsetting. With printing, tibbles only show the first 10 rows and all the columns that fit on a screen. In the printed report, the tibble shows the data type for each column in the output. For example, the abalone.df defined above is a tibble and printing it will result in the following:

## # A tibble: 4,177 x 9
##       sex length diameter height weight.whole weight.shucked
##    <fctr>  <dbl>    <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>
##  1      M  0.455    0.365  0.095       0.5140         0.2245
##  2      M  0.350    0.265  0.090       0.2255         0.0995
##  3      F  0.530    0.420  0.135       0.6770         0.2565
##  4      M  0.440    0.365  0.125       0.5160         0.2155
##  5      I  0.330    0.255  0.080       0.2050         0.0895
##  6      I  0.425    0.300  0.095       0.3515         0.1410
##  7      F  0.530    0.415  0.150       0.7775         0.2370
##  8      F  0.545    0.425  0.125       0.7680         0.2940
##  9      M  0.475    0.370  0.125       0.5095         0.2165
## 10      F  0.550    0.440  0.150       0.8945         0.3145
## # ... with 4,167 more rows, and 3 more variables: weight.viscera <dbl>,
## #   weight.shell <dbl>, rings <int>

With subsetting, if you want to pull out a single variable, the $ and [[]] are useful features. To extract a variable from a tibble by name, use $. To extract a variable by name or position, use [[]]. For example, to extract the height variable from the abalone data set, you refer to it by position:

as_tibble(abalone.df[[1]])
## # A tibble: 4,177 x 1
##     value
##    <fctr>
##  1      M
##  2      M
##  3      F
##  4      M
##  5      I
##  6      I
##  7      F
##  8      F
##  9      M
## 10      F
## # ... with 4,167 more rows

To use these in a pipe, youll need to use the special placeholder .:, as in abalone.df %>% .$x.

Also, compared to a data.frame, tibbles are more strict: they never do partial matching, and they will generate a warning if the column you are trying to access does not exist.
